      "writtenOn": "2016-08-01T18:12:10Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Not a question on your CL, just for my curiosity.  Is there a rationale for having the two very similar functions \"glWaitSync\" and \"glClientWaitSync\"?  Or is it just historical accident that can\u0027t now be cleaned up?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 19,
        "startChar": 5,
        "endLine": 19,
        "endChar": 15
      },
      "revId": "b529bec4812e9c40baf7b8b0ced2bbf8f57d4c1d",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cf8db5b7_c6b5339a",
        "filename": "distrib/android-emugl/host/libs/libOpenGLESDispatch/gles3_only.entries",
        "patchSetId": 61
      },
      "lineNbr": 19,
      "author": {
        "id": 1082465
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-08-01T19:32:12Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The two functions differ in how heavyweight the waiting is.\n\nglClientWaitSync will block the current CPU thread until the associated sync object has been signaled by the GPU.\n\nglWaitSync will allow the current CPU thread to continue and continue to queue up GPU commands, but only as far as the host GPU driver\u0027s user-facing command buffer, and stopping these GPU commands from being put on the host GPU driver\u0027s GPU-facing command buffer, until the sync object is signaled. Potentially, the CPU thread could then continue to do useful work while that\u0027s going on.\n\nThe second function isn\u0027t integrated yet, but the plan is to use it to implement the extension EGL_KHR_wait_sync in the system image. But, if we activate that extension, the system image\u0027s buffer swap system will go down a whole new code path that is untested and might require more changes in turn. The potential payoff would be better performance in SurfaceFlinger and any other apps that use it well.\n\nRef: https://www.opengl.org/wiki/Sync_Object",
      "parentUuid": "cf8db5b7_0c23bf61",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 19,
        "startChar": 5,
        "endLine": 19,
        "endChar": 15
      },
      "revId": "b529bec4812e9c40baf7b8b0ced2bbf8f57d4c1d",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cf8db5b7_29778807",
        "filename": "distrib/android-emugl/host/libs/libOpenGLESDispatch/gles3_only.entries",
        "patchSetId": 61
      },
      "lineNbr": 19,
      "author": {
        "id": 1099352
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-08-01T20:24:12Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "OK, thanks.  So glWaitSync always returns immediately, but will prevent other commands from getting to the GPU until the appropriate timeline is incremented, and the fence is signaled.\n\nHere\u0027s what remains confusing to me, about the intended uses.  If two client threads T0 and T1 are generating GL commands, which need to be executed in order (T0\u0027s commands, then T1\u0027s commands, say), there still needs to be synchronization that ensures that these threads issue the commands in the required order.  They could do other computations needed in support of the graphics commands in parallel, but the graphics commands themselves would need to be ordered.  Am I right that the Sync Object stuff is to prevent re-orderings that could otherwise happen *after* the commands had been issued, altering their order?",
      "parentUuid": "cf8db5b7_c6b5339a",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 19,
        "startChar": 5,
        "endLine": 19,
        "endChar": 15
      },
      "revId": "b529bec4812e9c40baf7b8b0ced2bbf8f57d4c1d",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cf8db5b7_57e9d413",
        "filename": "distrib/android-emugl/host/libs/renderControl_dec/renderControl.attrib",
